@jaraco: FYI, that approach will break some apps that currently use try to use the old backends explicitly. For example:

* https://bitbucket.org/pypa/wheel/src/tip/wheel/tool/__init__.py#__init__.py-50
* https://github.com/engla/kupfer/blob/master/kupfer/plugin_support.py#L171

Hi, thanks for posting the question. @aravindnc, thanks for your reply. As @aravindnc said, when defining a ruleset using JSON you cannot inline a function. The JSON definition is purely declarative. In the testdynamic.py example you can see how the Host::get_action function is overriden. durable_rules gives you the opportunity to resolve a rule function based on the action_name defined in the rule definition `run:` attribute.

I haven't documented the JSON format nor the host extensibility points because I didn't consider them as first class. Turns out the JSON dynamic rule scenario is much more useful than what I originally thought. Let me put some thought on how to make it first class.

```python
class Host(engine.Host):

    def __init__(self):
        super(Host, self).__init__()
        self._redis_server = redis.Redis()

    def get_action(self, action_name):
        def print_lamba(c):
            c.s.label = action_name
            print('Executing {0}'.format(action_name))

        return print_lamba;

    def load_ruleset(self, ruleset_name):
        ruleset_definition = self._redis_server.hget('rulesets', ruleset_name)
        if ruleset_definition:
            return json.loads(ruleset_definition)
        else:
            raise Exception('Ruleset with name {0} not found'.format(ruleset_name))

    def save_ruleset(self, ruleset_name, ruleset_definition):
        print('save ' + json.dumps(ruleset_definition))
        self._redis_server.hset('rulesets', ruleset_name, json.dumps(ruleset_definition))
```

