@miano Yes, the example you provided is an example of incorrect usage of the label. A label is similar to an ID, in that it uniquely identifies a piece of data in the file. The only differences are:

1. ID uniqueness is enforced by standard schema checkers; and
2. We use ID in places where other elements will reference them (via an IDREF) but labels in places where nothing else will reference them.

@aldanor — I assume the reason for not deriving from object and invoking `GetAttr` right away is that it's potentially expensive, but `if (obj.attr("foo")) ...` is a lightweight call (in that it invokes `HasAttr` rather than `GetAttr`): in other words, it *is* exactly your hypothetical `if (obj.hasattr("foo")) ...`.

So essentially `accessor` is a "pointer" class, in a loose sense, that doesn't do the heavy lifting until/unless you actually need it.  But following that, perhaps it would make sense to add dereference-like operators to it, such as:

```C++
object got;
object& operator*() { if (!got) { got = /* current code of operator object() */ } return got; }
object* operator->() { return &operator*(); }
// Backwards compatibility:
operator object() { return **this; }
template <typename T> T cast() const { return (*this)->cast<T>(); }
```
plus the operator() (and perhaps operator[]) overloads.  (Although it's not *quite* completely backwards compatible as the `operator object()` above isn't const—I suppose you could make them all const and change `got` to `mutable object got;`)

That seems a relatively easy way to get access to any named methods via `->` instead of `.`:

```C++
foo.attr("abc")->attr("def")->cast<MyType>();
```
without having to duplicate all the named methods of `object` (and wouldn't need any changes if new methods are added to `object`/`handle`).

You can call via:
```C++
(*foo.attr("abc")->attr("ghi"))("some", "args", "here");
```

Or if you add the forwarding-to-object operator() overloads:
```C++
foo.attr("abc")->attr("ghi")("some", "args", "here");
```

