@fafhrd91 (Clarifying my previous comment.) You may well be right that some developers use Transfer-Encoding as part of an application protocol. But even if they do use this horrible and unreliable hack, it would have to start with the server-side developers. Client-side developers can't just decide to rely on Transfer-Encoding if the server doesn't promise anything special about the chunks it sends, and breaks content into chunks at arbitrary boundaries.

My point was that Docker is certainly a well-behaved server. Perhaps @Anvil  only used Docker as an example, and if so, I'd be interested to know which real-world server they actually had trouble with.

BTW, all the libraries I've seen that parse multiple JSON objects obtained from chunked HTTP either [use state](https://github.com/jonnyreeves/chunked-request#writing-a-custom-chunk-parser) to work correctly, or [rely on delimiters](https://github.com/eBay/jsonpipe#prerequisites).

@asvetlov 
Well, with wildcard import you hit another problem: linters don't like them as like as people and both has good reasons againt this. 

The problem I raise is the same as yours: forbid imports of private things (: But at import system level, not at IDE hints one. For example, in Erlang there are no imports, but only exports: each module defines what others can reference and that's public API while everything rest is private. For Python we have `__all__` which filters what wildcard could import, but why not to filter direct imports as well? And yes, I know, that's a dream that won't get real in Python, but I think it's a good one (:

